Sinn Fein confirmed that the Irish nationalist party's deputy leader, Mary Lou McDonald, became the only candidate to replace outgoing leader Gerry Adams at the party's national meeting on Saturday. She will be confirmed in the position at a special party gathering on February 10. McDonald, 48, has been a member of Sinn Fein, a republican party in both the Republic of Ireland and Northern Ireland which is part of the United Kingdom, since 2004. She became Adams' deputy in 2009 and has been a member of the lower house of the Irish parliament since 2011. "For us in Sinn Fein in the time ahead, we have to grow our party, not just our mandate but also our capacities. We have to modernize, we have to be fit for purpose, fit for our task," McDonald said in a speech to party members in Belfast. Send  Facebook   Twitter   Google+   Whatsapp   
