  Tumblr   linkedin   stumble   Digg   reddit   Newsvine Permalink http://p.dw.com/p/2o9FW "As we enter a new era, we look ahead with confidence as a party that is about being in government here in the north, in government in the south also, working forward all the time for the realization of our ultimate goal of Irish unity." Adams, 69, announced in November he was stepping down as the party's leader after 34 years. He was a key figure in the Irish republican movement and played a major role in convincing the Irish Republican Army (IRA), a now-defunct paramilitary wing of the Sinn Fein party, to disarm as part of the Northern Ireland peace process. Read more: — London to set Northern Ireland budget, sparking concerns of direct rule — Northern Ireland power sharing talks stall "Sinn Fein in north and south" McDonald is a fresh face for the party as she has no historic links with the IRA, which was responsible for the deaths of 1,700 people during the conflict known as the Troubles in Northern Ireland. With McDonald's confirmation, the party will have female leaders in their 40s on both sides of the Irish border. Michelle O'Neill replaced former IRA commander Martin McGuinness in the Northern Ireland Assembly last year before his death in March. Sinn Fein is currently the third-biggest party in the Republic of Ireland and the second-biggest party in Northern Ireland. It still trails the center-right Fine Gael and Fianna Fail parties in opinion polls in the Republic of Ireland, but recent surveys suggest some voters would be more willing to vote for a party led by McDonald than Adams. "I want to see Sinn Fein in government north and south," McDonald said. "But it will be government based on equality, government that respects the rights of citizens, that delivers prosperity and opportunity for all and reflects our republican ideals." dv/jm (AFP, AP, Reuters)